highlights.description: sensitivity about being a Midwesterner
For Chris's immigrant family fleeing war in Columbia, the US was a place of hope
RuthAnn's discomfort, as a Chinese person, in small towns. Rooted in her childhood memory of being stared at in a small-town restaurant.
Wren on realizing the positive story she used to tell about living in Madison is just HER story.

The polarization in the Madison community along income and racial lines, and the racial disparity in particularly, is "a poisoning kind of pill to our democracy." The next two comments pick up on this.
Some hope. This opportunity to do something about the divide.
On the privileged motivation to "fix things" vis-a-vis the racial divide.
A lot of the work (that needs to be done) is "heart work". It's not something amenable to a  (quick) "fix."
There are a lot of "good hearted people" doing good work on the white-black thing. .But the university as a whole can "quite get its head" around it.
The university's "commodified, extractive way of looking at the world" makes it hard to break out of the existing system
The advent of rich students in Madison has changed the city in the last five to seven years.
The divide between those in higher ed institutions and the rest of the city (again, this is a Boston person)
Academics are trained to tear the other side's argument apart. There's a fundamental differnence between listening for understanding and just responding (for winning an argument).
We need to view our community as family. He says this with tears falling.
Our leaders need to listen to "the voices that they don't hear"
The woman who said there's no racism, people just don't know her story. She just wants people "to walk in my shoes for a minute."
Again, listening to stories should be paramount. It's not about finding "fixes".
Being different in a small town
Experience of getting stared at while traveling through a small town with parents
Wren introduction
UW employee struggling with academic incentives to listen to respond versus listening to understand. Should be prefaced with "Chris introduction."

Experience observing the increasing wealth of UW students and changes in housing in the city related to that. Should be prefaced by "Wren introduction" and paired with "Comments on decrease in homelessness and expansion of affordable housing."
